args:
The shikigami version of Gozu Tenno continues
to revive over and over, so the prince and his
party withdraw and question Seimei about his
cursed connection with Doman. Later that night,
Yoshitsune advocates the idea of living for
someone, which Seimei eventually warms to.
*pant* *pant* Yee-haw! We did it!\nWe went'n beat the darn thing!
Not so fast, fox. This is one of Doman's\nshikigami, and we are in a place\noverflowing with Yomi chi...
Damn! It absorbed the chi and revived!\nI guess that means we'll just have to\ntake it down again.
Enough. We will only wear ourselves out\nif we continue to struggle like this.
But if we don't get the mana back,\nGozu Tenno will—

Gozu Tenno is my pactwyrm, and so long
as I share as much mana with him as he
has lost, it will not be an issue.
Now stop being an idiot and withdraw!
O heavenly fox dashing through the sky,\ncome unto and deliver us beyond! Haaah!
Dear me. Gone as suddenly as you arrived,\nand without so much as a fare-thee-well?\nHow terrifically rude.
Ah, but your precious barrier is on\nthe verge of collapse, Seimei...
And the creation of the Underworld Key\nthat the Mukuroshu have sought for so\nlong is finally upon us...
This is your hideout... Did you bring us\nhere with your onmyodo?
Yes—and I hope you appreciate the gravity\nof the situation, because teleportation\ntalismans are exceedingly valuable!
How's Gozu doin', Lord Seimei?\nIs the big feller gonna pull through?
His power is weak, but he will survive.\nCarry him inside.
I've shared enough of my mana with him\nto replace what he lost, so he should\ncome around before long.
I'm happier'n a pig in fresh slop\nthat yer gonna be all right, Gozu!
Right then. Since we have a moment to\nbreathe, I think this is a good time for you\nto make with the explanations, Seimei.
Your objective wasn't to fulfill your duty\nas a Wyrmclan leader or gain revenge—\nit was to die in order to stop the curse.
That's a step beyond obsession. So what\nexactly happened between the two of you?

I can't believe I have to sit here and...
Tch. Fine. Guess there's no point in
trying to hide things now. I'll talk until
Gozu Tenno wakes up, at least.
This tale takes place back when my\ngrandfather was still at the head\nof the Ox Wyrmclan.

Doman was secretly engaged in forbidden
research at the Bureau of Onmyodo.
All his will was bent on learning the
ultimate in onmyodo powers.
What in the name'a mud were ya\ndoin' a fool thing like that for?!
Back then, I was eager to learn everything\nthere was to know about onmyodo—\nno matter the cost or danger.
After much work, I succeeded in reviving\na forbidden curse from an ancient tome.\nThe name of that curse...was Kodoku.
That's the thing ya said when you'n Doman\nwere goin' at it. What IS this Kodoku thing\nanyways? How's the darn thing even work?

One collects insects in a jar and lets them
feed on each another until one remains.
That survivor will then hold within it all the
hatred and spiritual power of the others.
This insect holds a tremendous power—the\nfell power of a thing which should not be.\nIt becomes, in essence, a living curse.
Just the thought of all those squirming\nbugs devouring each other is horrifying...
Ah, but it doesn't HAVE to be insects.\nThe curse can also be brought to life\nwith other creatures—including people.
People? Wait, Yoshitsune, you said there\nwere indications the curse had been used\nat the Bureau, yes? So does that mean...?
Exactly so. Doman carried out the Kodoku\ncurse inside the Bureau of Onmyodo.
It's an abhorrent notion, to be sure,\nbut also a terrifically effective one.

Even with insects, the curse is incredibly
potent. But if you do it with onmyoji,
the last one standing will achieve an
almost god-like amount of magical power.
And to achieve that, he was willing to\nbetray his colleagues and hex everyone\nto death?
How are we to stand against an enemy\nwho wields such a terrible power?
He doesn't have the power of Kodoku yet.\nNot until he kills the last onmyoji.
You're talking about yourself, aren't you?\nEr, but then why didn't he make a point\nto kill you when he had the chance?

I was in line to become the head of the
Ox Wyrmclan, which meant a soulpact and
a shortened lifespan. I suppose he was
willing to just let nature take its course.
Plus, leaving me alive gave him a rival of\nsorts to test his newfound powers against.
Why ain't ya just killin' HIM instead'a\ntryin' to off the both'a ya?!
Because, you stupid fox—if either one\nof us is left alive, the Kodoku curse will\nbe completed.
And a curse of such strength must not\nbe allowed to come into being.
That is why neither Doman nor myself\ncan remain alive.
Okay, I understand your role in this,\nbut how does Gozu Tenno fit in?
Gozu was my grandfather's pactwyrm\nback when the incident happened.
He was unable to prevent my grandfather's\ndeath, and has been wracked with regret\never since.
He wished to die alongside me in order\nto atone for failing to protect my family.\nThat's how we ended up together.
Heh. You're really at a loss, aren't you?

Your pactwyrm is on the verge of death,
and your disciple is begging you to live.
It's enough to make a man question his
grand plan to end it all, don't you think?
My own death is not an issue for me.\nI'm merely thinking about...them.
Is it truly all right to let him die with me?\nAnd what will happen to that stupid fox\nif I go and leave her all alone?
When you become a Wyrmclan leader,\nyou end up with responsibility for a lot\nof people—whether you like it or not.
Bold words for someone who appears \nnot to have a care in the world.
Heh. A fair point—although I meant what\nI said. As for me, I outlived those I was\nresponsible for a long time ago.
And how long ago was that, exactly?\nI've never been able to get a handle on\nyour past.

According to my grandfather's tales, the
Rooster Wyrmclan had no successor until
you sauntered back from the mainland
and suddenly took on the role.
You swore a soulpact to much fanfare,\nand became a Wyrmclan leader.\nIsn't that right?
You make it sound like a far greater deal\nthan it is. I inherited the clan because of\nmy blood ties. That's all.
Though it's true I was born in an era of\nstrife. I was urged on by my people, my\nvassals to fight until my very last breath.

An era of strife? Hinomoto has been at
peace for more than a hundred years.
The last turbulent time was before the
shogunate was even established!

It's just what it sounds like. All it takes is
the right combination of circumstances for
a person to find themselves with a body
that simply won't die. Ever.
Surely you aren't suggesting you're\nimmortal, right? Or that such a talent\neven exists in the first place?
It does—and I stand before you as proof.\nOh, I have seen so many things...
I have experienced partings and despair\nthat made me want to throw everything\naway—and yes, I have even tried to die.

But when I think back on it, the era of
conflict was a good one. I had a reason
to fight. I had friends. Those things alone
were more than enough to keep me going.

The pain of that burden and the happiness
that came from it were two sides of the
same coin. That is why life is as precious
as it is.
I have neither pain nor joy.
Liar. If you had nothing to be concerned\nwith, it wouldn't matter what happened\nto those two companions of yours.
Are you trying to lecture me into living?
Just thinking out loud, is all. I'm not the\nkind of woman who would try to sway you\none way or the other. It's your decision.
But I WILL say, the very fact of being alive\nnaturally makes us consider the thoughts\nand wishes of others.
Even if your intent was to live alone, you\nare not a lone onmyoji. They follow you—\na fact of which you are well aware.
So long as we live, we are caught up in\nthe bonds of obligation. That's rather a\ncurse in and of itself, don't you think?
Maybe. But it's one I don't mind having.
Heh. Has someone had a change of heart?
Perhaps living might not be so bad—\nand I bet I can figure out a way to\nbest Doman in the process...
